  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1214848973" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1214848973" />
    <a title="Kaitlin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19126246-kaitlin"><img alt="Kaitlin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1481663259p2/19126246.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1214848973?book_show_action=true">Mar 01, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kaitlin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kaitlin" href="/user/show/19126246-kaitlin">Kaitlin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780593046241" href="/book/show/2294069.Memories_of_Ice">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1214848973" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11044652065473666534">This book, this book... what to say about this book!? I&apos;ll start off with my overall thoughts of it and I&apos;d give this a 4.5* review overall because this is a much better written and more exciting and complicated and cool story than book 1 and 2. I felt that Gardens of the Moon was a really character focused story and there were real moments of wonder but there wasn&apos;t a lot of battle whereas Deadhouse Gates had nearly all battle focus and nowhere near as much time focusing on the characters. I fe</span>
  <span id="freeText11044652065473666534" style="display:none">This book, this book... what to say about this book!? I'll start off with my overall thoughts of it and I'd give this a 4.5* review overall because this is a much better written and more exciting and complicated and cool story than book 1 and 2. I felt that Gardens of the Moon was a really character focused story and there were real moments of wonder but there wasn't a lot of battle whereas Deadhouse Gates had nearly all battle focus and nowhere near as much time focusing on the characters. I felt that Book 3 was actually a great balance of the two of these books, good battle scenes which made a lot more sense to me and some really awesome moments of characters development and progression and sentimentality.<br /><br />This book follows two major storylines which entwine together as it goes on. The first storyline follows a group of 'ex-Malazan' soldiers who are being led by Dujeck Onearm and have a mission to go to war with the Panion Seer, a rather daunting task that will require a rather large amount of forging alliances and luck. The second storyline follows The Crippled God and the challenges that his active participation is going to bring to the mortals and magical beings of the Malazan world.<br /><br />This story follows a fair few characters once again, a lot of them are returning characters from the first book, Gardens of the Moon, and I was certainly happy about this because I felt that they were the ones I had connected with already and that it was an easy return to their storylines. <br /><br />Whiskeyjack and Paran were easy returns for me as each of their stories were interesting and enjoyable and I certainly love their characters. I definitely felt that each of them had their own personalities and they are thrown into some very tough and testing situations throughout the course of this book which really challenged and pushed them. We also got to see a little bit more of each of their personalities because we saw them have to enter a true, large scale battle against the Pannion Seer. We also get to see a little more of a gentle side and more emotional side for both of those characters and I felt that each of them were pushed further than they had been in the first book.<br /><br />Toc, Tool and Lady Envy were on a slightly different storyline where they were journeying through various Warrens and lands and I must say that their camaraderie and humour was a really uplifting and entertaining aspect of the story. I thought that each character was entertaining and individual in their own was and I feel like because I already knew a little of Toc and Tool they were wonderful to return to and understand further, plus their stories each take a huge amount of crazy turns I just didn't anticipate. Some of these twists are brutal, some are heartwarming and yet all are unexpected and startling.<br /><br />Some newer characters or characters who were not as major in the previous books but certainly became more prominent or more major in this book included:<br />- Silverfox, a young girl with an extraordinary amount of sway and power over the way that this book could go. She was a great addition to the book and I have no doubt that there is always more to come from characters in Malazan, and I feel like she could certainly be someone we could see more of. I loved her and hated her at different points within the book but I always felt for her and she really struggled her way through this book and some terrible and very trying situations.<br />- Gruntle who is a lowly Caravan Guard at the start of this story but quickly becomes a whole lot more than that. He certainly was a wonderful addition in that he gave us a reluctant leader character and I loved seeing him trying to fulfil his role and yet staying very down to earth :)<br />- Itkovian was a wonderful character who I didn't really like or even notice too much to begin with, but I then, let's just say, STUFF HAPPENS and he became an instant favourite character. I felt that there was so much in his story that was heartbreaking and pure and sad and happy all at once and I loved seeing him grow over the course of the book.<br /><br />Up until this point in the series we have seen Mortals, various races of different live and undead creatures and Gods but in this book we also get to meet some pretty badass character such as the Elder Gods who bring a whole new level of trouble to the game board. The Gods have been meddling in the world and playing with different characters the whole time, but now the Gods themselves are being played with too and my goodness there's a lot of crazy layers of plotting to follow :)<br /><br />One of the things which we actually found out a lot more about within this book was the Jaghuts, Barghasts, T'lann Imass, and Tiste Andii. Each of these races is totally and utterly unique and I loved getting to know a bit more about their personalities and backstory and past. <br />We also meet the K'Chain Che'malle and the Seguleh for the first time and let me say that both of these races are not really people that you'd want to meet or cross. Particularly the K'Chain Che'malle are a horrific dinosaur kind of creature with blades for hands.<br /><br />This book is a particularly bloody one in some areas and there are a few moments where I was in awe of how much chaos and blood there was. It's certainly a very grimdark book and there's a lot of 'grim' in this book, more so that book 1 &amp; 2 for sure! There's also a lot of very heartbreaking and sad moments, again a lot more so than in the first 2 books!<br /><br />Finally, why am I only giving this a 4.5*s if I liked everything so much? Because there was one story I didn't love as much as the others and it actually started to grate on me a little as I went through. That was the story of the Mhybe and whilst I do understand why Erikson made her the way she was, it just became irritating to me that she didn't put up more fight in her situation (horrific as it was).<br /><br />Other than that one storyline, everything wrapped up in a pretty intriguing and exciting way and I do think Erikson's writing by this book is a lot more on point, and exciting, than book 1 and 2. I am very much looking forward to book 4 next month and seeing where the storyline goes overall and maybe picking up some of the characters from Deadhouse again too. 4.5*s and certainly recommended if you can deal with very very complex and bloody storylines!</span>
  <a data-text-id="11044652065473666534" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


